TY  - JOUR
T1  - Directors' Multiple Identities, Identification, and Board Monitoring and Resource Provision
AU  - Hillman, Amy J.
AU  - Nicholson, Gavin
AU  - Shropshire, Christine
Y1  - 2008/06/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1080.0355
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1080.0355
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 441
EP  - 456
VL  - 19
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Scholars and practitioners are interested in board effectiveness, yet we know relatively little about directors' engagement in the boardroom. We integrate identity theory and social identity theory research with literature on board monitoring and resource provision to model how directors' multiple identities affect their behavior. We propose that directors' strength of identification with multiple identities affects the extent to which they engage in monitoring and resource provision. We discuss implications for corporate governance research and practice.
AB  - Scholars and practitioners are interested in board effectiveness, yet we know relatively little about directors' engagement in the boardroom. We integrate identity theory and social identity theory research with literature on board monitoring and resource provision to model how directors' multiple identities affect their behavior. We propose that directors' strength of identification with multiple identities affects the extent to which they engage in monitoring and resource provision. We discuss implications for corporate governance research and practice.
